4 A BILL FOR AN ACT ENTITLED: “AN ACT PROVIDING FOR THE USE OF EXPIRED OPIOID
5 ANTAGONISTS; PROVIDING PARTIAL IMMUNITY TO SCHOOL EMPLOYEES, TO ELIGIBLE RECIPIENTS,
6 AND TO MEDICAL PRACTITIONERS AND PHARMACISTS FOR USING EXPIRED OPIOID ANTAGONISTS;
7 AND AMENDING SECTIONS 20-5-426, 50-32-602, 50-32-607, AND 50-32-608, MCA.”
8
9 WHEREAS, it is the public policy of the state of Montana to encourage the administration and
10 distribution of opioid antagonists, including expired opioid antagonists, to save the lives of persons who suffer
11 opioid-related drug overdose events.
12
13 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF MONTANA:
14
15 Section 1. Section 20-5-426, MCA, is amended to read:
16 "20-5-426. Emergency use of opioid antagonist in school setting -- limit on liability. (1) A school,
17 whether public or nonpublic, may maintain a stock supply of an opioid antagonist to be administered by a
18 school nurse or other authorized personnel to any student or nonstudent as needed for an actual or perceived
19 opioid overdose. A school that intends to obtain an order for emergency use of an opioid antagonist in a school
20 setting or at related activities shall adhere to the following requirements:
21 (a) A school that stocks an opioid antagonist shall develop a protocol related to the training of
22 school employees, the maintenance and location of the opioid antagonist, and immediate and long-term
23 followup to the administration of the medication, including making a 9-1-1 emergency call.
24 (b) The opioid antagonist must be prescribed by a physician, advanced practice registered nurse,
25 or physician assistant. The school must be designated as the patient, and each prescription for an opioid
26 antagonist must be filled by a licensed pharmacy.
27 (c) The school shall provide training to authorized personnel. The training must include causes of
28 opioid overdose, recognition of signs and symptoms of opioid overdose, indications for the administration of an
