1 opioid antagonist, administration technique, and the need for immediate access to a certified emergency
2 responder. Training must be provided by a school nurse, certified emergency responder, or other health care
3 professional.
4 (d) The opioid antagonist must be kept in a secure and easily accessible location.
5 (e) A school nurse or other authorized personnel may, in good faith, administer the opioid
6 antagonist to any student or nonstudent who is experiencing a potential life-threatening opioid overdose based
7 on the protocol developed by the school.
8 (f) If a school stocks an opioid antagonist that has been prescribed to the school, that school shall
9 inform parents or guardians about the potential use of the opioid antagonist in an opioid overdose emergency.
10 The school shall make the protocol available upon request.
11 (g) A school district or nonpublic school and its employees and agents are not liable as a result of
12 any injury arising from the administration of an opioid antagonist, including an expired opioid antagonist, to a
13 student or nonstudent unless an act or omission is the result of gross negligence, willful or wanton misconduct,
14 or an intentional tort.
15 (2) For the purposes of this section, "opioid antagonist" means a drug that binds to opioid
16 receptors and blocks or inhibits the effect of opioids acting on those receptors, including but not limited to
17 naloxone hydrochloride or any other similarly acting drug approved by the United States food and drug
18 administration."
19
20 Section 2. Section 50-32-602, MCA, is amended to read:
21 "50-32-602. Purpose. The purposes of this part are to:
22 (1) save the lives of persons who have experienced an opioid-related drug overdose by providing
23 the broadest possible access to lifesaving opioid antagonist medication, including expired opioid antagonist
24 medication;
25 (2) facilitate the availability and use of opioid antagonist medication by providing professional, civil,
26 and criminal immunity to persons who prescribe, dispense, distribute, or administer an opioid antagonist; and
27 (3) encourage persons to seek medical treatment in an opioid-related drug overdose situation by
28 providing immunity from prosecution for certain criminal offenses for persons who seek or receive the medical
