3 Section 3. Section 50-32-607, MCA, is amended to read:
4 "50-32-607. Authorization for possession and administration of opioid antagonist -- reporting --
5 immunity related to expired opioid antagonist. (1) An eligible recipient to whom an opioid antagonist is
6 prescribed, dispensed, or distributed pursuant to 50-32-604 through 50-32-606 and who has received the
7 instruction and information provided for in 50-32-606 may do any of the following:
8 (a) possess and store the opioid antagonist. The storage of an opioid antagonist is not subject to
9 pharmacy practice laws or other requirements that apply to the storage of drugs or medications.
10 (b) in good faith, administer or direct another person to administer the opioid antagonist to a
11 person who is experiencing an actual or reasonably perceived opioid-related drug overdose; or
12 (c) distribute the opioid antagonist to a person who is an eligible recipient under 50-32-603(5)(a) or
13 (5)(b); and
14 (d) possess, store, administer, direct another person to administer, or distribute an expired opioid
15 antagonist.
16 (2) An eligible recipient to whom an opioid antagonist is dispensed pursuant to 50-32-604 through
17 50-32-606 shall report, if required by the department, information regarding the dispensing, distribution, and
18 administration of the opioid antagonist.
19 (3) A person who engages in the activities authorized in subsection (1) is not liable for injury or
20 damages caused by possessing, storing, administering, or directing another person to administer, or distributing
21 an expired opioid antagonist, except for injury or damages arising from gross negligence, willful or wanton
22 misconduct, or an intentional tort."
23
24 Section 4. Section 50-32-608, MCA, is amended to read:
25 "50-32-608. Professional conduct -- immunity. (1) A prescription issued pursuant to 50-32-604 or
26 50-32-605 is considered to have been issued for a legitimate medical purpose in the usual course of a
27 professional practice.
28 (2) Except for injury or damages arising from gross negligence, willful or wanton misconduct, or an
